All right, folks, welcome back.

00:10.600 --> 00:17.440
This is the seventh episode for the ICT mentorship on YouTube, 2022.

00:17.440 --> 00:22.440
This lecture is going to be dealing with daily bias and consolidation hurdles.

00:23.440 --> 00:28.440
All right, folks, welcome to the daily chart for the NASDAQ.

00:28.440 --> 00:37.440
And if you're looking at trading view under the NASDAQ selection, so it's the continuous contract.

00:37.440 --> 00:41.440
That way it makes all the candles look nice and crisp and you don't see any spotting.

00:41.440 --> 00:46.440
So right away, if you're looking at this, you should see this run on price taking out buy side liquidity.

00:46.440 --> 00:52.600
So all these relative equal highs here ran above it, then broke below a swing low.

00:52.600 --> 00:57.800
Created what? Here they got trades up into it.

00:57.800 --> 01:00.800
Now, where is it going to trade to?

01:00.800 --> 01:04.760
This low to this high midpoint, there's a gap right there.

01:04.760 --> 01:09.440
And they have the old low sell here.

01:09.440 --> 01:13.700
Aim here or here, and it runs it out.

01:13.700 --> 01:15.660
Now, this is important.

01:15.660 --> 01:19.100
Obviously, it sounds like, well, you know, you're cherry picking in a pack.

01:19.100 --> 01:21.360
Old moves. OK, that's how you learn.

01:21.360 --> 01:26.160
But think about what's happened on the daily chart.

01:26.160 --> 01:31.100
We traded below this low. We've taken sell side liquidity out of the marketplace.

01:31.100 --> 01:35.560
So with that, it's likely to retrace back up into the range.

01:35.560 --> 01:40.300
What's the range? This high to that low.

01:40.300 --> 01:43.560
But look closer. See how we have this nice energetic run?

01:43.560 --> 01:45.420
Look how many down close candles we have here.

01:45.420 --> 01:49.920
One, two, three, four. A lot of movement there.

01:49.920 --> 01:59.460
So I'm looking at this high and this low, and I'm trying to get a range for where we are at present.

01:59.460 --> 02:07.820
So once the sell side was taken out here, it's likely to retrace back inside the range of this high and this low.

02:07.820 --> 02:09.520
We've seen it come all the way back up.

02:09.520 --> 02:13.460
It went to a premium market, which is above equilibrium here.

02:13.460 --> 02:19.900
And then we went down below to a discount, bounced off of the old low here.

02:19.900 --> 02:24.460
Then we've consolidated around equilibrium.

02:24.460 --> 02:32.000
Now, when you have this condition, it can make it very difficult to get a true reading on bias.

02:32.000 --> 02:39.360
So there's times when even me as ICT, I don't have a good clear read on what it is I'm looking for.

02:39.360 --> 02:45.400
So I have to demand more price action and more information or Intel, as I like to call it,

02:45.400 --> 02:50.800
based on what the market's going to do right after the open at 930 in the morning New York time.

02:50.800 --> 02:57.860
For disclosure, in my own paid membership, I mentioned to them that I felt that this was a likely area

02:57.860 --> 03:01.900
where they could probably take it down and sweep that area.

03:01.900 --> 03:03.800
Whether it goes lower or not, it's irrelevant.

03:03.800 --> 03:14.040
But where we were here to here, that's what I was expecting some type of move last night for Tuesday's trading.

03:14.040 --> 03:18.640
OK, so Tuesday's trading, the 8th of February, 2022.

03:18.640 --> 03:23.300
Going into the marketplace, I was anticipating something that would be bearish.

03:23.300 --> 03:26.480
That's going to be useful to us when we go into the lower time frame charts,

03:26.480 --> 03:30.440
because I'm going to show you what I had to deal with this morning and how I had to overcome that.

03:30.480 --> 03:34.240
And this is something that if you're using these concepts and practice with your demo account,

03:34.240 --> 03:38.640
you're going to have these same conundrums and you have to find a way to overcome them.

03:38.640 --> 03:41.720
And I'm just going to suggest this to you here.

03:41.720 --> 03:45.320
But before we go into lower time frames, I want to teach bias.

03:45.320 --> 03:52.180
So if we have this set up on a daily chart, market structure has a shift lower trade up into a fair value gap

03:52.180 --> 03:55.720
until we get down to here and here each day.

03:55.720 --> 03:58.880
I'm anticipating lower prices.

03:58.920 --> 04:01.980
So my bias is bearish.

04:01.980 --> 04:05.260
Now, every single day is going to be a down close candle,

04:05.260 --> 04:12.120
but I'm going to hunt intraday price action with that in mind.

04:12.120 --> 04:16.320
If I'm going to take it long, it would be counter trend to that bias.

04:16.320 --> 04:18.480
My leverage is going to be dialed back.

04:18.480 --> 04:25.460
So let's assume for a moment that the account that I was trading with would allow me to trade 10 contracts.

04:25.460 --> 04:28.940
10 contracts would be the maximum I could trade.

04:28.940 --> 04:37.400
So if I'm trading with the bias, which would be bearish during the run from here to here and here,

04:37.400 --> 04:46.460
then I'm going to look to utilize the maximum leverage that I can have without over leveraging based on a fixed percentage basis.

04:46.460 --> 04:48.660
Like I like three and a half percent.

04:48.660 --> 04:50.960
I'm not telling you to use three and a half percent.

04:50.960 --> 04:55.560
You should be risking less than one percent, about a half percent or a quarter percent,

04:55.560 --> 05:02.760
because if you don't know what you're doing, there's no reason to be putting higher levels of risk behind a move if you don't know what it is that you're doing.

05:02.760 --> 05:10.240
It's going to create toxic thinking, bad habits, and you're going to be afraid to execute based on the results you're getting.

05:10.240 --> 05:12.160
So you want to be indifferent to the results.

05:12.160 --> 05:19.240
That in the beginning is important by having a demo account using very, very low leverage, if not deleveraging.

05:19.240 --> 05:24.220
And I'll talk a little bit about that when we get into money management, but that's not this topic.

05:24.220 --> 05:38.580
So from this high down to that low, each day I'm going in with the expectation that it's going to likely set up a sell scenario where I can get short and hopefully buy back at a lower price.

05:38.580 --> 05:48.120
Count how many updates or green candles there are from this high and this high down to that low.

05:48.120 --> 05:54.000
One, two. Real important.

05:54.000 --> 05:59.120
So the delivery by the algorithms are spooling.

05:59.120 --> 06:03.860
That means prices expanding and going directionally one way.

06:03.860 --> 06:09.400
When that occurs, there's going to be times where you have an up close candle.

06:09.400 --> 06:13.200
That may be a day that you tried to go short and maybe you've lost.

06:13.200 --> 06:17.000
OK, no big deal. Same thing going into the next day, going in for looking for shorts.

06:17.040 --> 06:19.080
Next day, same thing, same thing.

06:19.080 --> 06:25.940
And then here it opens and trades down below the low and has a huge expansion move and then comes back above.

06:25.940 --> 06:35.380
And that's it. It closes on the near the high of the day or midpoint of the body in this area here.

06:35.380 --> 06:41.000
Is there a lot of up close candles during that bias being bearish?

06:41.000 --> 06:48.240
No. You need to get over the concern about being right every single time.

06:48.240 --> 06:53.540
You need to put aside also the idea of perfection because you're not going to have it perfect.

06:53.540 --> 06:56.280
You're not going to get in perfectly. You're not going to get out perfectly.

06:56.280 --> 06:58.440
You're not going to have the perfect amount of contracts.

06:58.440 --> 07:04.480
You're not going to have the perfect asset.

07:04.480 --> 07:13.460
In other words, you may be trading the NASDAQ and the E-Mini S&P has a little bit better run and delivers a little bit more highly unlikely, but vice versa.

07:13.460 --> 07:18.180
You get what I'm saying. So you're always going to find reasons to be wrong.

07:18.180 --> 07:24.680
Embrace imperfection. Embrace the idea that you don't have to know everything.

07:24.680 --> 07:30.120
You don't have to be right. OK, being right is not equivalent to being profitable.

07:30.120 --> 07:32.260
Very important factor there.

07:32.260 --> 07:40.260
So with bias, in short, you're looking at your daily chart to get a read on where it's likely to go to next year.

07:40.260 --> 07:44.160
Where's the price going to draw? Is it going to draw higher to an old high?

07:44.160 --> 07:52.260
Is it going to draw down to an old low? And until it gets that high or low, you stay with that bias.

07:52.260 --> 07:57.960
OK, so it's a quick down and dirty way of interpreting price action for daily bias.

07:57.960 --> 08:07.860
But the folks that I've taught that are hung up on daily bias, really what they're trying to say is, and this is exactly what they're getting at,

08:07.860 --> 08:13.200
but they can't either articulate or they just won't be honest with it or me.

08:13.200 --> 08:23.500
What they want is tell me how to get the high of the day when it's bearish and how to get out at the low and get all the move and never take a loss.

08:23.500 --> 08:31.840
And avoid when it's going to be a day that goes against me where I feel uncomfortable.

08:31.840 --> 08:39.540
Now, that might sound extreme, and maybe some of you that have issues with daily bias are thinking to yourself, that's not me.

08:39.540 --> 08:45.440
I just want to know when it's going to go up, when it's going to go down. I'm telling you, if you strip it down, that's what you're trying to do.

08:45.440 --> 08:52.940
You're trying to demand that I give you some magic bullet that's going to give you the absolute highest high and the lowest low

08:52.980 --> 09:01.340
on the bearish and bullish days. So that way, you're trading perfectly. I don't trade perfectly. No one trades perfectly.

09:01.340 --> 09:12.140
So you have to have this embracing of the gray area in the marketplace. That gray area is where things aren't always so clear.

09:12.140 --> 09:19.340
But because of experience you've had in the past, seeing things unfold the way they hopefully would if you've been trained properly,

09:19.340 --> 09:29.380
then there's nothing to fear. Even if you do it wrong and you have a adverse reaction or result to taking a trade using the logic that you're training with,

09:29.380 --> 09:39.080
there's no reason to be fearful because one or two or maybe a small string of losing trades does not in any way, shape or form diminish the effectiveness of a model

09:39.120 --> 09:52.120
if it's based on sound logic. So you're going to utilize the daily chart to determine whether or not the next candle is going to be likely bullish or bearish.

09:52.120 --> 10:03.380
Between this high here in the midpoint of this low to high, I'm expecting down close candles. That would equate to a bearish bias.

10:03.380 --> 10:10.580
It doesn't mean that I can't take a long entry. It just means that if I do take a long entry into today, I'm going to do it with far less leverage.

10:10.580 --> 10:20.020
And if I see a setup that's bearish, I'll use or consider using, not always, but I'll consider using my maximum risk, which is four and a half percent.

10:20.020 --> 10:25.520
But I like to see trades that I feel comfortable with with three and a half percent.

10:25.520 --> 10:33.460
And until we get down to this low and underneath it, that means it's likely to reverse or consolidate and we have a retracement back in.

10:33.460 --> 10:42.760
So once it starts doing this and it's hanging around equilibrium, it gets very difficult even for me to determine a bias.

10:42.760 --> 10:51.620
So what does that mean? No trading? No, it just means that you have to rely on the smaller time frame intraday charts and just simply look for liquidity pools.

10:51.620 --> 11:00.020
So you're going to trade intraday volatility, running old highs, running out old lows, being a lot more nimble.

11:00.020 --> 11:11.480
And like a surgical strike, you take your handles or your points that you're trying to get out of the marketplace and then run.

11:11.480 --> 11:17.880
You don't try to overstay your welcome. So let's go down to a lower time frame.

11:17.880 --> 11:25.740
All right, so we have the 15 minute time frame and we have our 830 in the morning crosshairs here.

11:25.740 --> 11:33.140
Crosshairs are the vertical line that denotes the time that we start looking back to the left.

11:33.140 --> 11:37.440
Right here, go to the left, we see this is our first low.

11:37.440 --> 11:43.840
So we mark that and right in here, first to the left is here.

11:43.840 --> 11:50.240
We don't want to use this low by itself because it's inside of this candle.

11:50.240 --> 11:56.840
So I want to use the extreme. Where's the liquidity going to be? Is it going to be above this or is it going to be above that? It's going to be above this, OK?

11:56.840 --> 12:04.700
Why? Why not that one? And why this one? Keep looking left. What do you see over here?

12:04.700 --> 12:11.640
See that? These are relative equal highs. What does retail traders see that as? Resistance.

12:11.640 --> 12:16.240
So they see it going up to here, stopping and going lower. They see it going up to here, failing to go up here.

12:16.240 --> 12:20.700
So now they think this is a really strong resistance level.

12:20.700 --> 12:27.640
And it went lower. Look at that. Then the market showed how that level was real resistance by going right through it.

12:27.640 --> 12:32.400
But this would be a first target here to reach for.

12:32.400 --> 12:38.240
And if you want to use a longer term intraday, the target would be back here.

12:38.240 --> 12:43.100
Because to the left of this one is this one, which essentially is the same.

12:43.100 --> 12:52.600
Then we have this one here, OK? So obviously with the benefit of hindsight, you can see that we traded below that low here.

12:52.600 --> 13:00.040
Then we reversed and started going higher. We took out this high here, which I traded this.

13:00.040 --> 13:05.740
I did not hold for this. Now, the question is going to be, is why didn't you hold it for that one ICT?

13:05.840 --> 13:14.340
Well, if you look at the range from this high down to the low over here,

13:14.340 --> 13:19.100
about midpoint is just above this high, right?

13:19.100 --> 13:22.040
Then we have this little imbalance right there.

13:22.040 --> 13:25.100
So what about I'm teaching you in this mentorship?

13:25.100 --> 13:30.640
I'm looking for about the midpoint and some kind of liquidity.

13:30.640 --> 13:33.500
There's buy stops above that, OK?

13:33.500 --> 13:36.900
So we traded below. I went along on that candle.

13:36.900 --> 13:42.200
